===Etymology===
1620 (referring to a {{l|en|bedbug}}); from earlier {{term|bugge||beetle|lang=en}}, conflation of (1) {{etyl|enm}} {{term|bugge||scarecrow, hobgoblin|lang=enm}}, from {{proto|gem-pro|bugja-||swollen up, thick}} (liken Norwegian {{term|bugge||big man|lang=no}}, Low German dialect {{term|Bögge||goblin, snot|lang=nds}}; and (2) {{etyl|enm}} {{term|budde||beetle|lang=enm}}, from Old English {{term|budda|lang=ang}} (see {{term|scearnbudda||dung beetle|lang=en}}), from {{proto|gem-pro|buddōn}} (liken Low German {{term|Budde||louse, grub|lang=nds}}, Norwegian {{term|budda||newborn domestic animal|lang=no}}). More at {{l|en|bud}}.

